{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513882"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:15:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:15:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12246"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583654"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:23:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:23:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12246"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12246"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.14,0.18,0.03,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4768"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29983"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4768"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15948"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7607"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18788"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46370"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/29983"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61\u2010year\u2010old man presents to the emergency department with a three day history of sudden onset of blurry vision. He has never had any previous visual problems. His medical history includes rheumatoid arthritis, hypertension, and diabetes mellitus. His medications include perindopril and metformin. On examination his blood pressure is 130/90 mmHg, pulse 90/min, temperature 37.3\u02daC, respiratory rate 18/min and Sa02 98% on room air. Nothing abnormal is found on visual acuity or fundoscopy, but a visual field defect is identified. He has a left sided homonymous sectoranopia. The rest of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Damage to which one of the following structures is most likely to have produced this clinical picture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lateral geniculate nucleus","Medial geniculate nucleus","Medial portion of the ventral posterior nucleus","Ventral anterior/lateral nuclei","Lateral portion of the ventral posterior nucleus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn homonymous sectoranopia is a wedge-shaped defect located near the horizontal meridian, either pointed at fixation or sparing fixation. This is characteristic of a lateral geniculate body lesion (usually secondary to an ischaemic event). These are relatively unusual visual field defects and these visual field patterns are based on the lateral geniculate body\u0027s dual blood supply from the anterior and posterior choroidal arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroanatomy of the visual pathways:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELateral geniculate nucleus\u0026nbsp;\u2014\u0026nbsp;80% of the nerve fibers in the optic tract project into the ipsilateral lateral geniculate nucleus in the thalamus. Other optic tract fibers innervate the Edinger-Westphal nuclei in the pretectum, providing the afferent limb for the pupillary light reflex. The axons from the ipsilateral eye terminate in the second, third, and fifth laminae of the lateral geniculate nucleus, while the axons from the contralateral eye terminate in the first, fourth, and sixth laminae. The nerve fibers then form a precise retinotopic map in the lateral geniculate nucleus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOptic radiations\u0026nbsp;\u2014\u0026nbsp;The neurons originating from the lateral geniculate nucleus form the optic radiations or the geniculocalcarine tract and end in the primary visual cortex in the occipital lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClinical features of lateral geniculate nucleus lesion:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn lateral geniculate nucleus lesions, visual field defects are variable in nature because of their intricate retinotopic organization. The nature of the visual field defect is also influenced by the underlying cause. Vascular lesions of the lateral geniculate nucleus usually produce congruous and characteristic visual field defects. Occlusion of the posterior choroidal artery causes a wedge defect that straddles the horizontal meridian region (sectoranopia), while occlusion of the anterior choroidal artery spares that sector of visual field (sector-sparing).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pupillary reactions in patients with lesions of the lateral geniculate nucleus are normal unless there is the involvement of the optic tract or the brachium of the superior colliculus, which produces a contralateral relative afferent papillary defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with lesions of the lateral geniculate nucleus may also show signs and symptoms suggestive of damage to the ipsilateral thalamus (contralateral hemihypoesthesia, abnormal referred pain on the contralateral side) and/or pyramidal tract (contralateral motor weakness).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith regards to the rest of the options provided in this question, the following is a list of the thalamic nuclei and their functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral geniculate nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for \u003Cstrong\u003Evision\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedial geniculate nucleus is responsible for auditory signals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedial portion of the ventral posterior nucleus is responsible for facial sensation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVentral anterior/lateral nuclei is responsible for motor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELateral portion of the ventral posterior nucleus is responsible for body sensation (touch, pain, proprioception, pressure, vibration)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lateral geniculate nucleus is responsible for vision"],"references":["MD GS. Thalamic nuclei [Internet]. Kenhub. Kenhub; 2022 [cited 2022Nov11]. Available from: https://www.kenhub.com/en/library/anatomy/thalamic-nuclei","Liu A, Sanguino L. Right lateral geniculate nucleus infarct presenting as a left monocular temporal hemianopia. Clinical Case Reports. 2019 May 14;7(6):1226\u20139.","UpToDate [Internet]. www.uptodate.com. [cited 2022 Nov 12]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/homonymous-hemianopia?search=Homonymous%20hemianopia\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~19\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1#H14"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15948"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12246"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/15948"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-11-13T09:48:3